words.def: Abstract - An indicator applied to a classifier (e.g., actor, class, use case) or to some features of a classifier (e.g., a class's operations) showing that the feature is incomplete and is intended not to be instantiated, but to be specialized by other definitions.
words.name: Abstract

words.def: Abstract class - A class that does not provide a complete declaration, perhaps because it has no implementation method identified for an operation. By declaring a class as abstract, one intends to prohibit direct instantiation of the class. An abstract class cannot directly instantiate objects; it must be inherited from before it can be used.
words.name: Abstract class

words.def: Abstract operation - Unlike attributes, class operations can be abstract, meaning that there is no provided implementation. Generally, a class containing an abstract operation should be marked as an abstract class. An Operation must have a method supplied in some specialized Class before it can be used.
words.name: Abstract operation

words.def: Abstraction is the process of picking out common features and deriving essential characteristics from objects and procedure entities that distinguish it from other kinds of entities.
words.name: Abstraction

words.def: Action - An action is the fundamental unit of behaviour specification and represents some transformation or processing in the modeled system, such as invoking a method of a class or a sub activity
words.name: Action

words.def: Action sequence -
words.name: Action sequence

words.def: Action state -
words.name: Action state

words.def: Action steps -
words.name: Action steps

words.def: Activation - the time during which an object has a method executing. It is often indicated by a thin box or bar superimposed on the Object's lifeline in a Sequence Diagram
words.name: Activation

words.def: Activity diagram - a diagram that describes procedural logic, business process or work flow. An activity diagram contains a number of Activities and connected by Control Flows and Object Flows.
words.name: Activity diagram

words.def: Active class - a class defining active objects
words.name: Active class

words.def: Active object - an object running under its own thread
words.name: Active object

words.def:
Activity - carrying out behaviour in a State machine diagram

Do - a type of Activity which may be interrupted, as opposed to normal Activities which may not be interrupted
Internal - an Activity that is executed within a State

Entry - an Activity that is executed when a State is entered
Exit - an Activity that is executed when a State is exited
words.name: Activity

words.def: Do - a type of Activity which may be interrupted, as opposed to normal Activities which may not be interrupted
words.name: Do

words.def:
Internal - an Activity that is executed within a State

Entry - an Activity that is executed when a State is entered
Exit - an Activity that is executed when a State is exited
words.name: Internal

words.def: Entry - an Activity that is executed when a State is entered
words.name: Entry

words.def: Exit - an Activity that is executed when a State is exited
words.name: Exit

words.def: Activity final - the end point of an activity diagram. When a thread reaches an Activity Final node, all the threads of the activity terminate. (Contrast with Flow Final node, which marks the end of one thread.)
words.name: Activity final

words.def: Actor - a role that a user takes when invoking a use case. Also see actor modeling.
words.name: Actor

words.def: Aggregation - 1. a special type of association used to represent a stronger relationship between two classes than a regular association; typically read as "owns a", as in, "Class A owns a Class B". A hierarchy of classes where the child object may or may not continue to exist if the parent object is destroyed; see 'composition'. 2. An aggregation is a structural relationship that specifies that one class represents a large thing which constitute of smaller things and represents "has-a" relationship.
words.name: Aggregation

words.def: Artifact - items that model physical pieces of information in your system, such as a user's manual, training material, or password file
words.name: Artifact

words.def: Association - 1. a relationship with 2 or more ends, where each end is on a class (or other classifier). Each end is called a Role, and may have a role name, Multiplicity, and may be Navigable. 2. An association is a structural relationship that specifies that the objects of one thing are connected with the objects of another.
words.name: Association

words.def: Association class - a class that describes an association.
words.name: Association class

words.def: Asynchronous - The sender of an asynchronous message does not wait for a response.
words.name: Asynchronous

words.def: Attribute - a significant piece of data owned by a Class, often containing values describing each instance of the class. Besides the attribute name and a slot for the attribute value, an attribute may have specified Visibility, Type, Multiplicity, Default value, and Property-string.
words.name: Attribute

words.def: Block - Block is a place where all the aggregates are collected at one place
words.name: Block

words.def: BPM - Business Process Model, is used to define the process followed by the business. It is a high level design for the business process.
words.name: BPM

words.def: BPMN - Business Process Modelling Notations, are used to define the process on paper with the help of predefined shapes of UML.
words.name: BPMN

words.def: Call -
words.name: Call

words.def: Cardinality - the current number of occurrences of a Property. The cardinality must be a value that is allowed by the multiplicity
words.name: Cardinality

words.def: Child -
words.name: Child

words.def: Class - the primary declarative construct of Object-Oriented Programming; a cohesive unit of Attributes and Operations; a compile-time template for an Object
words.name: Class

words.def: Class diagram - a type of static structure diagram that describes the structure of a system by showing the system's classes, their attributes and the relationships between the classes.
words.name: Class diagram

words.def: Classifier - a category of UML elements that have some common features, such as attributes or methods.
words.name: Classifier

words.def: Client -
words.name: Client

words.def: Collaboration - A collaboration is a society of classes,interfaces and other elements that work together to provide some cooperative behavior that is bigger than the sum of its parts.
words.name: Collaboration

words.def: Communication diagram
words.name: Communication diagram

words.def: Component - A component represents a software module (source code, binary code, executable, DLL, etc.) with a well-defined interface. The interface of a component is represented by one or several interface elements that the component provides. Components are used to show compiler and run-time dependencies, as well as interface and calling dependencies among software modules. They also show which components implement a specific class.
words.name: Component

words.def: Component diagram
words.name: Component diagram

words.def: Composite structure diagram
words.name: Composite structure diagram

words.def: Composition - a specific type of relationship describing how one Object is composed of another Object; a form of Aggregation where the child object is destroyed if the parent object is destroyed.
words.name: Composition

words.def: Condition -
words.name: Condition

words.def: Connection -
words.name: Connection

words.def: Constraint - natural language, programming language or Object Constraint Language boolean condition which may not be false if a Class is to be considered valid
words.name: Constraint

words.def: Containment - containment by value and containment by reference. Containment by value implies that an object contains another object; containment by reference implies that an object contains a pointer to another object.
words.name: Containment

words.def: Decision - a point in an Activity diagram where a Flow splits into several, mutually exclusive, Guarded flows. A Merge marks the end of the optional behaviour started by the Decision
words.name: Decision

words.def: Dependency - a dependency exists between two defined elements if a change to the definition of one would result in a change to the other. In UML this is indicated by a line pointing from the dependent to the independent element.
words.name: Dependency

words.def: Deployment diagram
words.name: Deployment diagram

words.def: Derived property - a property that can be calculated or inferred from other properties
words.name: Derived property

words.def: Diagram - a visual representation of a subset of features of a UML Model
words.name: Diagram

words.def: Directed relationship -
words.name: Directed relationship

words.def: Domain - a logical grouping that explicitly declares a rule which defines ownership of objects based upon some type or property.
words.name: Domain

words.def: Edge - a synonym for Flow
words.name: Edge

words.def: Encapsulation - a means to bind together code and the data it uses. It is the basis of object oriented programming.
words.name: Encapsulation

words.def: Entity -
words.name: Entity

words.def: Enumeration - a set of constant values for a new data type
words.name: Enumeration

words.def: Event - when it occurs on an Object it may cause a Transition in a State machine diagram
words.name: Event

words.def: Expansion region - a set of Actions in an Activity diagram that occur once for each of a collection of input Tokens to the Expansion Region
words.name: Expansion region

words.def: Extend - a means to use a class as a starting point for creation of a new class. The new class inherits all of the attributes, properties, and methods of the class it extends.
words.name: Extend

words.def: Exception -
words.name: Exception

words.def: File -
words.name: File

words.def: Final state - the state at which an object ceases to exist
words.name: Final state

words.def: Flow - a navigational connection between two Actions
words.name: Flow

words.def: Flow Final - the point at which a Flow ends without ending the complete Activity
words.name: Flow Final

words.def: Fork - a point in an Activity diagram where a Flow of logic splits into several concurrent Flows (Threads)
words.name: Fork

words.def: Found Message - starting point for a Sequence diagram
words.name: Found Message

words.def: Generalization - a relationship between a specific classifier (typically a class) to a more general classifier asserting that the general classifer contains common features among both the specific classifier and the general classifier. Features include, for example, properties, and constraints. The use of generalization is often logically restricted to cases where the specific classifier is a "kind-of" or "sort-of" the general classifier: for example, a Boxer is a "kind-of" Dog. When the classifiers involved are software engineering classes, generalization usually involves reusing code; it is often implemented using inheritance, where the more specific code reuses the more general code.
words.name: Generalization

words.def: Generalization Tree - Several specialized classifiers may point to the same general classifier, forming a generalization tree, where the general classifer contains common features shared by all the specialized versions. As generalization is a relationship, it is possible for a classifer to participate in several generalizations, often being on the specific end or on the general end, forming a directed acyclic graph (DAG) (i.e., no loops).
words.name: Generalization Tree

words.def: Generic -
words.name: Generic

words.def: Guard - a boolean test that must be satisfied for a Flow of an activity diagram or a Transition of a state machine diagram to be allowed to start
words.name: Guard

words.def: Hierarchy -
words.name: Hierarchy

words.def: History pseudostate - points to the initial state of an object where no previous state history was saved
words.name: History pseudostate

words.def: Inheritance - where a new more specific Class derives part of its definition from an existing more general Class
words.name: Inheritance

words.def: Initial node - the start point of an Activity diagram
words.name: Initial node

words.def: Initial pseudostate - points to the initial State of an Object
words.name: Initial pseudostate

words.def: Instance - An instance is a concrete manifestation of an abstraction to which a set of operations can be applied and which has a state that stores the effect of the operation.
words.name: Instance

words.def: Interaction diagram
words.name: Interaction diagram

words.def: Interaction overview diagram
words.name: Interaction overview diagram

words.def: Interaction Frame - a section of a Sequence diagram, divided into fragments, which is subject to an algorithmic Operator such as iteration, parallelism or optionality.
words.name: Interaction Frame

words.def: Interface - a defined communication boundary.
words.name: Interface

words.def: Join - a point in an activity diagram where several concurrent flows (threads) synchronize, waiting until all are complete before continuing with a single flow
words.name: Join

words.def: Lifeline - indicates a participating Object or Part in a Sequence diagram. The Lifeline may show activation, Object creation, and Object deletion.
words.name: Lifeline

words.def: Link - a relationship between objects. While an Object is an instantiation of a Class a Link can be seen as an instantiation of an Association.
words.name: Link

words.def: Merge - a point in an Activity diagram marking the end of the optional behavior started by a Decision
words.name: Merge

words.def: Message - a signal from one object (or similar entity) to another, often with parameters. Often implemented as a call to a Method, including the Constructor and Destructor, of an Object in a Sequence diagram.
words.name: Message

words.def: Method -
words.name: Method

words.def:
Modeling -

Domain - the representation of real world conceptual entities
Design - the representation of software Classes and Interfaces
Dynamic - use of Interaction diagrams to describe collaborations and behavior
words.name: Modeling

words.def: Domain - the representation of real world conceptual entities
words.name: Domain

words.def: Design - the representation of software Classes and Interfaces
words.name: Design

words.def: Dynamic - use of Interaction diagrams to describe collaborations and behavior
words.name: Dynamic

words.def:
Multiplicity - 1. A specification of the number of possible occurrences of a property, or the number of allowable elements that may participate in a given relationship. In UML 1.x, it was also possible to have a discrete list of values, but this was eliminated in UML 2.0. 2. It specifies how many objects may be connected across an instance of an association which is written as a range of values(like 1..*).

Mandatory - A required multiplicity, the lower bound is at least one, usually 1..1 or 1
Optional - The lower bound is at most zero, usually, 0..1
Many - A multiplicity with no upper limit, either 0..* or *
Forbidden - No elements allowed, 0..0 (in UML 2.2)
words.name: Multiplicity

words.def: Mandatory - A required multiplicity, the lower bound is at least one, usually 1..1 or 1
words.name: Mandatory

words.def: Optional - The lower bound is at most zero, usually, 0..1
words.name: Optional

words.def: Many - A multiplicity with no upper limit, either 0..* or *
words.name: Many

words.def: Forbidden - No elements allowed, 0..0 (in UML 2.2)
words.name: Forbidden

words.def: Namespace - a context in which an identifier exists.
words.name: Namespace

words.def: Navigable - the ability for objects of a Class at one end of an Association to retrieve Objects from the other end. Associations need not be navigable.
words.name: Navigable

words.def: Node -
words.name: Node

words.def: Note - It is an explanatory part of UML models. A note is a symbol for rendering constraints and comments attached to an element or collection of elements.
words.name: Note

words.def: Object - a runtime instance of a Class. Objects are rarely shown on diagrams (because there are usually too many) unless they are used to illustrate some scenario, test, etc. Such Objects are often shown with the Attributes of the Class populated with sample data
words.name: Object

words.def: Object Constraint Language (OCL) - a declarative language for describing rules and constraints that apply to UML models
words.name: Object Constraint Language (OCL)

words.def: Object diagram
words.name: Object diagram

words.def: Operation - the signature of a Method of a Class; consists of the Operation Name, Visibility, Parameter list, Return Type, and Property-string
words.name: Operation

words.def:
Operator - an algorithmic feature of Interaction Frame that defines the behavior of that frame. Examples include:

alt - multiple alternatives each with a guard condition. Only one alternative can be true.
critical - a fragment within a larger parallel Interaction Frame that when entered suspends the interleaving of events from the other fragments.
loop - the fragment iterates according to a guard condition.
neg - an invalid interaction.
opt - single alternative with a guard condition.
par - each fragment is run in parallel.
ref - an interaction defined in another diagram.
strict - a fragment with the ordering of reception events across multiple lifelines follow strictly their graphical arrangement.
words.name: Operator

words.def: alt - multiple alternatives each with a guard condition. Only one alternative can be true.
words.name: alt

words.def: critical - a fragment within a larger parallel Interaction Frame that when entered suspends the interleaving of events from the other fragments.
words.name: critical

words.def: loop - the fragment iterates according to a guard condition.
words.name: loop

words.def: neg - an invalid interaction.
words.name: neg

words.def: opt - single alternative with a guard condition.
words.name: opt

words.def: par - each fragment is run in parallel.
words.name: par

words.def: ref - an interaction defined in another diagram.
words.name: ref

words.def: strict - a fragment with the ordering of reception events across multiple lifelines follow strictly their graphical arrangement.
words.name: strict

words.def: Package - A package is a collection or grouping of related classes or of classes with related functionality.
words.name: Package

words.def: Package diagram
words.name: Package diagram

words.def: Parameter - data passed in a Message to be used within the Method
words.name: Parameter

words.def: Partition - section of an Activity diagram or Sequence diagram occupied by a single Class or Object
words.name: Partition

words.def: Pin - a parameter of an Action
words.name: Pin

words.def: Polymorphism - the ability of Objects belonging to different Classes to respond to Operations of the same name, each one according to the right Class-specific behaviour
words.name: Polymorphism

words.def: Profile - Provides a generic extension mechanism for building UML models. Other extension mechanisms include stereotypes.
words.name: Profile

words.def: Property - an Attribute or an Association
words.name: Property

words.def: Property-string - a qualifier for Attributes and Operations. Examples include {ordered}, {readonly}, {unique}.
words.name: Property-string

words.def: Qualified association - tightens the multiplicity or role of an association between 2 classes by dividing the set of objects into subsets based on a value of the qualifier—an attribute of the target objects, association objects, or some a derived attribute of the target or association objects.
words.name: Qualified association

words.def: Realization - Realization shows the relationship between an Interface and the class that provides the implementation for the interface.
words.name: Realization

words.def: Reference -
words.name: Reference

words.def: Request - The input to the system for finding the related abstracts from different operations (Add, Del, Mod, Inq.). Request could be for only one for every operation
words.name: Request

words.def: Response - The output of the "Request". Response could be 1 or more for a single request.
words.name: Response

words.def: Relation -
words.name: Relation

words.def: Return - a reply that may be issued from a Method following a Message
words.name: Return

words.def: Role - description of the part played in an Association by one of the Classes in the Association
words.name: Role

words.def: Scenario - a narrative describing foreseeable interactions
words.name: Scenario

words.def: Self-call - a Message from an Object to one of its own Methods
words.name: Self-call

words.def: Sequence diagram - describes the Messages sent between a number of participating Objects in a Scenario
words.name: Sequence diagram

words.def: Signal - an Event which can occur in an Activity diagram in three different ways: as a Time Signal, as a signal which an Activity can listen for and a signal which an Activity can send
words.name: Signal

words.def: State - an Object exists at one of the States described in a State machine diagram. A state encompasses all the properties of the object along with the values of each of these properties.
words.name: State

words.def: State diagram - synonym for State machine diagram
words.name: State diagram

words.def: State machine diagram - describes the lifetime behaviour of a single Object in terms of in which State it exists and the Transition between those States
words.name: State machine diagram

words.def: Static attribute - an attribute that does not relate to a specific object but is at class level; that is, an attribute that is common among all objects of that class
words.name: Static attribute

words.def: Static modeling - use of class diagrams to describe structure
words.name: Static modeling

words.def: Static operation - an operation that does not relate to a specific object but is at class level
words.name: Static operation

words.def: Stereotype - a notation allowing the extension of UML symbols. Some are defined within Profiles. Examples of predefined UML stereotypes are Actor, Exception, Powertype and Utility.
words.name: Stereotype

words.def: Structure diagram
words.name: Structure diagram

words.def: Superstate - construct allowing several States which share common Transitions and Internal Activities
words.name: Superstate

words.def: Swim lane - synonym for Partition
words.name: Swim lane

words.def: System model - The logical UML model being represented through one or more UML diagrams
words.name: System model

words.def: Tagged values - In extensibility
words.name: Tagged values

words.def: Template - a Class that accepts a compile-time parameter defining the Type to be used within the Class; often to implement Collections of any Type
words.name: Template

words.def: Thread - a sequence of instructions whose execution is being scheduled by the Operating System and may run in parallel with other threads
words.name: Thread

words.def: Timing Diagram
words.name: Timing Diagram

words.def: Token - symbolises the Thread of an Activity diagram
words.name: Token

words.def: Transition - 1. movement from one State to another in a State machine diagram. The transition is specified by its Trigger-signature [Guard]/Activity 2. a relationship between two states indicating that when a specific event occurs and specific conditions are satisfied an object in the first state will perform certain action(s) and enter the second state.
words.name: Transition

words.def: Type - the options are: an elementary Value type such as integer, string, date, or Boolean or a Reference type defined in a Class
words.name: Type

words.def: Use case - A use case can be defined as a sequence of actions, including variations, that the system can execute and that produce an observable result which has some value for an actor that interacts with the system
words.name: Use case

words.def: Use case diagram
words.name: Use case diagram

words.def: Uses dependency -
words.name: Uses dependency

words.def:
Visibility - the availability for access of elements in a model. Typically used to limit the visibility of features defined by a Class (e.g., attributes, operations). When applied to features defined by a class, the standard options are:

private (-): available only within the Class in which it was defined. This is the most limited visibility
protected (#): available within any subclass of this class and within the package which directly contains the defining Class
package (~): available only within the Package which directly contains the defining Class
public (+): available to any Class that can see the defining Class. This is the least limited visibility.
words.name: Visibility

words.def: Workflow - Set of sequential steps which must be done to get a job done
words.name: Workflow

words.def: XMI - An OMG standard for exchanging metadata information via Extensible Markup Language (XML).
words.name: XMI

words.def: xUML - an UML profile or generic extension mechanism for customizing Unified Modeling Language (UML).
words.name: xUML
